WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:05.000
This video from the W3C Web Accessibility Initiative

2
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.120
introduces some of the tools and techniques that people with disabilities use to interact with the web. 

3
00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:15.040
Some use specialized software or hardware, called assistive technology.

4
00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:19.000
Others adapt standard software or hardware to better meet their needs.

5
00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:23.880
Perception - hearing, feeling and seeing.

6
00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:26.320
When content is accessible,

7
00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:28.360
people can perceive it through different senses,

8
00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:30.800
depending on their needs and preferences.

9
00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:31.760
For example,

10
00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:33.360
some people who can't see a screen

11
00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:34.400
or hear audio,

12
00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:35.920
rely on websites and apps

13
00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:37.120
that can present the information

14
00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.600
in different ways.

15
00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:39.960
People who are blind may

16
00:00:39.960 --> 00:00:41.240
use assistive technology

17
00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:43.000
on computers and mobile phones

18
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:44.680
called screen readers.

19
00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:46.000
These software tools

20
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.320
read the information on the screen out loud,

21
00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:50.560
or they can present it in braille.

22
00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:52.400
Bird.

23
00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:53.560
Birds are a group of warm-blooded vertebrates

24
00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:54.720
constituting the class Aves,

25
00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:55.400
(/’eIvi:z/)

26
00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.840
characterised by feathers, toothless beaked jaws, the laying of

27
00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:00.240
Screen readers process websites and apps

28
00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:01.920
with correctly coded headings,

29
00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:06.400
lists, links, buttons, and other structures much better.

30
00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:08.840
People who are blind rely on hearing or touch,

31
00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:10.440
rather than sight.

32
00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:11.280
For video,

33
00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:12.720
content creators need to ensure

34
00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:14.360
that visual information is provided

35
00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:16.720
in auditory form as well.

36
00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:19.560
Often these descriptions

37
00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:21.040
of visual information can be placed

38
00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:23.080
in existing pauses in the audio,

39
00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.440
or the script can be created

40
00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:26.280
from the start with sufficient description

41
00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:28.040
of the scenes, characters,

42
00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:30.120
and other important visual information.

43
00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:32.280
People who are deaf-blind

44
00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:35.080
also use screen readers to present the information

45
00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:36.440
using a device called a

46
00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:38.800
Refreshable Braille display.

47
00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:40.520
Braille characters are a combination

48
00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:42.040
of raised or lowered dots,

49
00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:43.880
which people read by scanning over them

50
00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:45.520
with their fingertips.

51
00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:48.320
Similarly to people who are blind and deaf-blind,

52
00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:50.640
people who are Deaf or hard of hearing

53
00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:52.920
may use haptic feedback too;

54
00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.600
for example, through vibration alerts on a mobile phone

55
00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:57.640
instead of auditory notifications.

56
00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:00.200
People who are Deaf or hard of hearing

57
00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:02.920
often rely on seeing instead of hearing.

58
00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:04.760
For example, while watching a video

59
00:02:04.760 --> 00:02:07.000
they may use captions or sign language

60
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.240
as an alternative to the audio.

61
00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:12.160
You can help

62
00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:16.000
make technology

63
00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:18.000
accessible

64
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:19.280
to me.

65
00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:25.080
Accessibility: It's about people. 

66
00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:29.480
Presentation: distinguishing

67
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.200
and understanding.

68
00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:35.120
When content is accessible,

69
00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.760
people can adjust its presentation to make it easier

70
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:39.560
to distinguish and understand.

71
00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:41.000
This could include adjusting

72
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:42.200
screen size and color

73
00:02:42.200 --> 00:02:43.320
to see better,

74
00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:44.600
adjusting audio volume

75
00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:46.400
to hear better, or adjusting

76
00:02:46.400 --> 00:02:49.480
how text is presented to read it better.

77
00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:52.520
Some people with low vision

78
00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:53.600
increased the text size

79
00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:55.360
to make it easier to read.

80
00:02:55.360 --> 00:02:56.560
They might adjust properties

81
00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:58.760
in the web browser or operating system,

82
00:02:58.760 --> 00:02:59.720
such as increasing

83
00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:00.960
the default text size,

84
00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:02.080
font type, and line

85
00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:04.080
spacing to better see the text.

86
00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:06.520
Websites and apps that are programmed

87
00:03:06.520 --> 00:03:08.520
and designed to adapt to these properties,

88
00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:10.280
allow people to use the content

89
00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:11.880
without the text overlapping,

90
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:12.960
getting cropped,

91
00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:14.320
or requiring them to scroll

92
00:03:14.320 --> 00:03:17.040
both vertically and horizontally.

93
00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:19.920
Other people with low vision

94
00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:21.560
increase everything on the screen,

95
00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:23.120
not only text.

96
00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:25.480
They might use screen magnification software

97
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:27.640
as a digital magnifying glass.

98
00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:29.440
Some might also change the text

99
00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:30.440
and background colors

100
00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:31.920
to better read the text

101
00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:33.200
and text-to-speech

102
00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:36.000
to hear the text while they're reading.

103
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.520
This means that websites and apps

104
00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:39.080
need to be programmed and designed

105
00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:41.240
to allow people to change the colors

106
00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:42.400
rather than forcing them

107
00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:44.560
to appear in a certain way.

108
00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:48.040
Presentation is not only visual.

109
00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:50.600
People with auditory disabilities, for example,

110
00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:51.600
might need to increase

111
00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:53.120
the volume of online meetings

112
00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:54.880
and multimedia like videos,

113
00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:56.360
podcasts and music,

114
00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.160
without increasing the volume of other

115
00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:01.080
system sounds like notification alerts.

116
00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:02.280
Adjusting the bass,

117
00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:04.000
treble and balance of the sound

118
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
can make the audio easier to hear,

119
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.320
so operating systems and media players

120
00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:10.080
need to provide these settings.

121
00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:11.520
Also, these settings work

122
00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.040
better with high quality audio

123
00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:15.080
that does not have background noise.

124
00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:17.760
Presentation adjustments

125
00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:19.240
can also make content easier

126
00:04:19.240 --> 00:04:20.400
to focus on,

127
00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:21.440
particularly for people

128
00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:23.000
with different types of cognitive

129
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.600
and learning disabilities.

130
00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:26.160
This includes “reading modes”

131
00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.440
that hide less relevant parts of the content,

132
00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:30.600
such as sidebars and front matter;

133
00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:32.040
pop up and animation blockers

134
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:33.320
that help avoid distraction

135
00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:34.440
and interruption;

136
00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:36.040
and digital reading rules

137
00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:36.840
that help readers

138
00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:39.320
focus on one line at a time.

139
00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:41.920
Some reading assistants,

140
00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:42.960
for example, those that 

141
00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:44.880
some people with dyslexia might use

142
00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:46.520
adjust how the text is presented

143
00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:48.480
to make it easier to read.

144
00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.200
This includes changing the font type,

145
00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:52.000
text size, colors

146
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:53.720
and the spacing between letters,

147
00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:55.760
sentences and paragraphs.

148
00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:58.240
Some people read better with serif-type fonts

149
00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:00.280
and others with sensory fonts.

150
00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:02.360
Adjusting these properties are individual

151
00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:03.920
from one person to another,

152
00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:05.000
which is why flexible

153
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.160
design is so important.

154
00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:09.800
Other reading assistants

155
00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:11.360
support comprehension.

156
00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:12.720
Some can process a text

157
00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:14.600
to simplify words and phrases,

158
00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:16.240
and sometimes also simplify

159
00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:17.920
complex sentences.

160
00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:19.280
These tools rely on proper

161
00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:22.280
programming and design to work.

162
